1
00:02:59,242 --> 00:03:00,573
Excuse me?

2
00:03:03,246 --> 00:03:05,476
Come on, honey.
Let's get you ready for bed.

3
00:03:18,295 --> 00:03:19,956
I am no one special.

4
00:03:20,530 --> 00:03:25,331
Just a common man with common thoughts.
I've led a common life.

5
00:03:26,036 --> 00:03:30,439
There are no monuments dedicated to me,
and my name will soon be forgotten.

6
00:03:31,041 --> 00:03:32,531
But in one respect,

7
00:03:32,676 --> 00:03:36,237
I've succeeded as gloriously as
anyone who ever lived.

8
00:03:36,379 --> 00:03:38,472
-Looking good, Duke.
-Feeling good.

9
00:03:38,615 --> 00:03:41,516
I've loved another
with all my heart and soul...

10
00:03:41,651 --> 00:03:44,449
...and for me that has always
been enough.

11
00:03:44,588 --> 00:03:46,078
How's it hanging, Harry?

12
00:03:46,223 --> 00:03:48,589
I keep trying to die,
but they won't let me.

13
00:03:48,725 --> 00:03:50,818
Well, you can't have everything.

14
00:03:54,097 --> 00:03:54,961
Big day today.

15
00:03:55,098 --> 00:03:57,532
You say that every day,
you old devil.

16
00:03:59,202 --> 00:04:02,694
lt's a lovely day outside.
Let's take a walk.

17
00:04:03,273 --> 00:04:04,501
I don't think so.

18
00:04:04,641 --> 00:04:06,939
Well, we've got to get you out
of this room.

19
00:04:07,177 --> 00:04:10,112
Come on now, honey.
Some fresh air would do you good.

20
00:04:10,247 --> 00:04:11,111
Hello?

21
00:04:13,183 --> 00:04:15,378
I'm sorry. lt's not a good day.

22
00:04:15,518 --> 00:04:17,645
I don't think she's up for anything.

23
00:04:17,787 --> 00:04:19,084
Hello?

24
00:04:20,156 --> 00:04:21,623
This is Duke.

25
00:04:21,758 --> 00:04:23,521
He's come to read to you.

26
00:04:24,227 --> 00:04:25,524
Read?

27
00:04:27,731 --> 00:04:29,392
No.

28
00:04:29,532 --> 00:04:30,556
I don't know.

29
00:04:30,700 --> 00:04:35,034
Oh, come on. You'll like him.
He's Very funny.

30
00:04:49,085 --> 00:04:52,577
All right, now.
Where did we leave off?

31
00:04:53,456 --> 00:04:56,619
Oh, yeah, yeah, I know.
lt was the night of the carnival.

32
00:04:56,760 --> 00:04:59,524
Noah was there
with his friends Fin and Sara.

33
00:04:59,663 --> 00:05:02,029
-Noah?
-That's where they met.

34
00:05:02,866 --> 00:05:05,858
June sixth, 1940.

35
00:05:06,436 --> 00:05:08,802
Allie was 1 7 years old.

36
00:05:09,506 --> 00:05:11,406
Little man wins a prize.

37
00:05:11,541 --> 00:05:13,406
-Thank you for playing.
-You're real funny.

38
00:05:13,743 --> 00:05:14,903
Man, I clobbered that thing.

39
00:05:15,045 --> 00:05:16,603
I'm telling you, these games are fixed.

40
00:05:16,746 --> 00:05:17,576
Hello.

41
00:05:18,415 --> 00:05:20,508
Hi. What's your name?

42
00:05:28,358 --> 00:05:31,623
-Who's this girl with Sara?
-Her name's Allie Hamilton.

43
00:05:31,761 --> 00:05:33,786
She's here for the summer
with her family.

44
00:05:33,930 --> 00:05:35,727
Dad's got more money than God.

45
00:05:35,865 --> 00:05:37,594
-Hi, Fin!
-Hi, honey.

46
00:05:37,901 --> 00:05:39,095
Look, I won you a prize.

47
00:05:39,235 --> 00:05:42,398
Fin, thank you!

48
00:05:50,714 --> 00:05:52,648
You want some cotton candy?

49
00:05:57,987 --> 00:05:59,352
You want to dance with me?

50
00:05:59,689 --> 00:06:00,678
No.

51
00:06:00,824 --> 00:06:02,052
Why not?

52
00:06:02,192 --> 00:06:03,625
Because I don't want to.

53
00:06:03,760 --> 00:06:06,593
Noah, she's with us.

54
00:06:06,730 --> 00:06:08,721
Allie, you want
to ride the Ferris wheel?

55
00:06:09,432 --> 00:06:10,421
Good idea.

56
00:06:10,567 --> 00:06:12,194
-I'd love to.
-All right.

57
00:06:12,702 --> 00:06:13,794
Excuse me.

58
00:06:15,238 --> 00:06:16,170
Excuse me.

59
00:06:21,444 --> 00:06:23,605
-Noah Calhoun.
-What?

60
00:06:23,747 --> 00:06:26,113
Works down at the lumberyard with Fin.

61
00:06:29,119 --> 00:06:31,519
He was about two inches away
from my face.

62
00:06:31,654 --> 00:06:34,020
Yeah, I saw. That's Noah, though.

63
00:06:35,692 --> 00:06:37,057
You know,
I'm surprised he even came over.

64
00:06:37,193 --> 00:06:38,820
I think he likes you.

65
00:06:59,449 --> 00:07:00,882
-Hey quit it, you jerk!
-Get off me!

66
00:07:01,017 --> 00:07:02,678
Have you flipped your lid?!

67
00:07:04,254 --> 00:07:06,381
What are you doing?

68
00:07:06,523 --> 00:07:09,924
-You can't do that!
-I'll pay you when I get down, Tommy!

69
00:07:10,059 --> 00:07:11,424
I'm Noah Calhoun.

70
00:07:11,561 --> 00:07:13,688
-So?
-So it's really nice to meet you.

71
00:07:13,830 --> 00:07:16,196
-Allie, who is this guy?
-I don't know. Noah Calhoun.

72
00:07:16,332 --> 00:07:18,960
-I would really like to take you out.
-Friend, do you mind?

73
00:07:20,403 --> 00:07:23,065
You can't sit more than two people
in a chair, Noah!

74
00:07:23,206 --> 00:07:24,434
Okay, Tommy. All right.

75
00:07:27,877 --> 00:07:30,641
Get down, Noah!
You're going to kill yourself!

76
00:07:30,780 --> 00:07:32,077
Noah, cut it out.

77
00:07:32,215 --> 00:07:33,648
Well, will you go out with me?

78
00:07:33,783 --> 00:07:34,841
What?

79
00:07:34,984 --> 00:07:36,451
No!

80
00:07:36,586 --> 00:07:38,053
-Never?
-No!

81
00:07:38,321 --> 00:07:40,755
-Why not?
-Hey, pal, she just told you.

82
00:07:40,890 --> 00:07:43,723
-Why not?
-I don't know, because I don't want to.

83
00:07:44,727 --> 00:07:47,127
You leave me no other choice, then.

84
00:07:48,031 --> 00:07:48,690
Oh, my God.

85
00:07:48,832 --> 00:07:51,596
-Stop fooling around!
-What are you doing?

86
00:07:51,734 --> 00:07:54,100
-Noah, grab the bar!
-I'll ask you one more time.

87
00:07:54,471 --> 00:07:57,565
Will you or will you not go out
with me?

88
00:07:58,541 --> 00:07:59,872
Goddamn, my hand's slipping.

89
00:08:00,009 --> 00:08:01,670
Then grab the bar, you idiot!

90
00:08:01,811 --> 00:08:03,073
Not until she agrees.

91
00:08:03,213 --> 00:08:04,271
Go out with him.

92
00:08:04,414 --> 00:08:06,746
-Fine! I'll go out with you.
-What?!

93
00:08:06,883 --> 00:08:09,181
-No, don't do me any favors.
-No! I want to!

94
00:08:09,319 --> 00:08:10,843
-You want to?
-Yes!

95
00:08:10,987 --> 00:08:12,648
-Say it.
-I want to go out with you!

96
00:08:12,789 --> 00:08:15,189
-Say it again.
-I want to go out with you!

97
00:08:15,725 --> 00:08:17,522
All right, all right, we'll go out.

98
00:08:18,127 --> 00:08:20,220
You think you're so smart, don't you?

99
00:08:20,363 --> 00:08:22,058
That wasn't funny, you idiot!

100
00:08:22,198 --> 00:08:24,359
Oh, it's okay. I'll take care of this.

101
00:08:25,768 --> 00:08:27,167
What are you doing?

102
00:08:27,303 --> 00:08:28,167
Please don't do that.

103
00:08:28,538 --> 00:08:31,302
-Don't do that.
-I can't believe it.

104
00:08:32,141 --> 00:08:33,005
Oh, God.

105
00:08:35,078 --> 00:08:37,444
You're not so cocky now, are you?

106
00:08:37,780 --> 00:08:39,247
I'll get you for that.

107
00:08:39,382 --> 00:08:41,441
Maybe you will, maybe you won't.

108
00:08:45,121 --> 00:08:46,315
Oh, will you look at that.

109
00:08:47,590 --> 00:08:49,080
lt's that girl from the carnival.

110
00:08:51,694 --> 00:08:52,854
You remember me?

111
00:08:53,596 --> 00:08:58,226
Yeah, sure. Mr. Underwear, was it?
How could I forget?

112
00:08:58,368 --> 00:08:59,528
Yeah, I'm really sorry about that.

113
00:08:59,669 --> 00:09:03,867
lt was really stupid to crawl up
the Ferris wheel to talk to somebody.

114
00:09:04,007 --> 00:09:05,474
But I had to be next to you.

115
00:09:06,743 --> 00:09:08,643
I was being drawn to you.

116
00:09:10,880 --> 00:09:15,544
Oh, jeez. What a line.
You use that on all the girls?

117
00:09:15,985 --> 00:09:16,952
No.

118
00:09:17,086 --> 00:09:19,953
Right. I saw you the other night
with Little Miss Ribbons.

119
00:09:20,089 --> 00:09:21,954
-What are you doing tonight?
-What?

120
00:09:22,091 --> 00:09:23,558
Or tomorrow night, or this weekend.

121
00:09:23,693 --> 00:09:25,888
-Why?
-Why? Our date.

122
00:09:26,029 --> 00:09:28,054
-What date?
-The date you agreed to.

123
00:09:28,197 --> 00:09:31,064
-No.
-You did. You promised and you swore it.

124
00:09:31,200 --> 00:09:33,532
Well, I guess I changed my mind.

125
00:09:34,504 --> 00:09:37,905
I know you get a dirty guy coming up
to you you don't know,

126
00:09:38,041 --> 00:09:39,838
you don't know me. But I know me.

127
00:09:41,844 --> 00:09:46,406
And when I see something that I like,
I got to h-- I love it.

128
00:09:47,016 --> 00:09:49,746
-I go crazy for it.
-What are you talking about?

129
00:09:51,054 --> 00:09:52,282
Well, you.

130
00:09:54,524 --> 00:09:55,855
-You're good.
-What?

131
00:09:55,992 --> 00:09:58,984
-You're good.
-No. You're getting me wrong.

132
00:09:59,128 --> 00:10:02,620
You're fantastic. You really are.
I'm impressed.

133
00:10:02,765 --> 00:10:05,359
-I'm not usually like this. I'm sorry.
-Oh, yes, you are.

134
00:10:06,035 --> 00:10:08,094
I can be funny if you want.

135
00:10:08,237 --> 00:10:09,966
Pensive.

136
00:10:10,206 --> 00:10:11,298
Smart.

137
00:10:11,841 --> 00:10:13,308
Superstitious.

138
00:10:13,710 --> 00:10:14,802
Brave.

139
00:10:15,044 --> 00:10:16,875
And I could be light on my feet.

140
00:10:17,480 --> 00:10:18,742
I could be whatever you want.

141
00:10:20,183 --> 00:10:22,617
Tell me what you want
and I'll be that for you.

142
00:10:24,287 --> 00:10:25,311
You're dumb.

143
00:10:27,557 --> 00:10:28,421
I could be that.

144
00:10:31,961 --> 00:10:33,929
Come on, one date.
What's it going to hurt?

145
00:10:34,564 --> 00:10:35,963
I don't think so.

146
00:10:36,199 --> 00:10:38,030
What can I do to change your mind?

147
00:10:38,167 --> 00:10:39,828
Guess you'll figure something out.

148
00:10:41,604 --> 00:10:42,901
-Are you sure she's coming?
-Relax.

149
00:10:43,039 --> 00:10:46,873
lt's all set up. We're meeting them for
the late show. Look. What'd I tell you?

150
00:10:53,750 --> 00:10:56,480
Oh, my goodness. What a coincidence!

151
00:10:56,619 --> 00:11:01,852
Look who's here.
Allie, you remember Noah, don't you?

152
00:11:01,991 --> 00:11:03,185
Yes, I remember.

153
00:11:03,826 --> 00:11:04,884
Come here.

154
00:11:05,028 --> 00:11:06,325
-Hi.
-Hi.

155
00:11:06,462 --> 00:11:08,862
-lt's nice to see you again.
-You too.

156
00:11:09,198 --> 00:11:11,223
-You look great.
-Oh, thanks.

157
00:11:11,367 --> 00:11:13,232
Really, really great.

158
00:11:13,369 --> 00:11:15,769
You do look great. You look great.
And I know I look great.

159
00:11:15,905 --> 00:11:17,930
So can we please go see this movie?

160
00:11:18,074 --> 00:11:19,507
Show's about to start.

161
00:11:20,343 --> 00:11:21,367
After you.

162
00:11:21,878 --> 00:11:26,076
-You come back here, Li'l Abner!
-You ain't going to catch me, Daisy Mae!

163
00:11:26,215 --> 00:11:28,649
lt's Sadie Hawkins Day,
I'm supposed to catch you!

164
00:11:28,785 --> 00:11:32,016
-I'm faster than you!
-Oh, get over here.

165
00:11:32,155 --> 00:11:34,180
No! No! No!

166
00:11:34,323 --> 00:11:35,790
I'll get you!

167
00:11:37,860 --> 00:11:38,952
Go on and git!

168
00:11:39,996 --> 00:11:41,293
Here I come!

169
00:11:53,209 --> 00:11:55,837
You catch-um Polecat fair and square.

170
00:12:01,484 --> 00:12:02,473
Wait for me!

171
00:12:04,187 --> 00:12:05,586
What happened in that movie?

172
00:12:07,590 --> 00:12:09,683
-Here you go.
-Thank you.

173
00:12:11,794 --> 00:12:13,455
-What are you guys doing?
-Want to walk with me?

174
00:12:13,596 --> 00:12:14,688
-Get in.
-What's going on?

175
00:12:15,598 --> 00:12:16,428
We'll walk.

176
00:12:16,566 --> 00:12:17,760
You guys love each other?

177
00:12:20,169 --> 00:12:22,933
-I get it. You guys do love each other.
-Don't do anything I wouldn't do.

178
00:12:23,840 --> 00:12:24,704
Okay, goodbye.

179
00:12:24,841 --> 00:12:25,967
All right.

180
00:12:26,542 --> 00:12:27,531
All right.

181
00:12:31,748 --> 00:12:32,840
That was fun.

182
00:12:35,218 --> 00:12:36,947
I haven't seen a movie in ages.

183
00:12:37,620 --> 00:12:38,416
Really?

184
00:12:38,554 --> 00:12:41,079
Not since I was a little kid.

185
00:12:42,291 --> 00:12:43,417
What?

186
00:12:43,960 --> 00:12:48,260
I'm busy. I don't have a lot of time.

187
00:12:49,866 --> 00:12:51,299
You're busy?

188
00:12:52,101 --> 00:12:53,591
I have a very strict schedule.

189
00:12:54,737 --> 00:12:56,170
My days are all planned out.

190
00:12:56,539 --> 00:12:57,904
I get up in the morning.

191
00:12:58,040 --> 00:13:01,567
Breakfast, math tutor,
Latin tutor, lunch...

192
00:13:01,711 --> 00:13:04,475
...tennis lesson, dance lesson,
sometimes both.

193
00:13:04,614 --> 00:13:08,141
French tutor, piano lesson,
then I eat dinner.

194
00:13:08,284 --> 00:13:09,808
After dinner I spend time
with my family

195
00:13:09,952 --> 00:13:13,319
and then I catch up on some reading.

196
00:13:18,895 --> 00:13:21,762
-Sounds like the road to success.
-You bet.

197
00:13:22,431 --> 00:13:24,956
I'm applying to all these colleges.

198
00:13:25,601 --> 00:13:28,536
Radcliffe, Sarah Lawrence.
Those are the ones we want.

199
00:13:30,306 --> 00:13:31,364
And who's ''we''?

200
00:13:32,308 --> 00:13:33,240
What?

201
00:13:33,376 --> 00:13:35,139
You just said, ''The ones that we want.''

202
00:13:35,578 --> 00:13:38,274
Oh.Mama and Daddy.
We decide everything together.

203
00:13:40,349 --> 00:13:41,816
Everything?

204
00:13:42,518 --> 00:13:46,386
No, not everything.
But the important things, yes.

205
00:13:47,623 --> 00:13:51,024
And everything else you get
to decide all by yourself?

206
00:13:52,495 --> 00:13:53,723
Don't be rude.

207
00:13:53,863 --> 00:13:55,125
I'm sorry.

208
00:13:58,034 --> 00:14:00,059
Just trying to figure out
what you do for fun.

209
00:14:01,137 --> 00:14:02,331
What do you mean?

210
00:14:04,173 --> 00:14:05,697
I mean...

211
00:14:06,609 --> 00:14:07,405
I don't know,

212
00:14:07,543 --> 00:14:09,670
...all those things are things you
have to do, right?

213
00:14:10,847 --> 00:14:12,678
So, what do you do because
you want to?

214
00:14:14,650 --> 00:14:16,049
I just told you.

215
00:14:19,689 --> 00:14:21,020
I don't know.

216
00:14:21,624 --> 00:14:23,057
You're surprising me.

217
00:14:24,393 --> 00:14:25,223
What?

218
00:14:25,361 --> 00:14:27,522
I always figured you were kind of....

219
00:14:28,998 --> 00:14:30,158
Kind of what?

220
00:14:30,867 --> 00:14:32,198
Just...

221
00:14:34,036 --> 00:14:35,264
...free.

222
00:14:35,404 --> 00:14:36,837
What?

223
00:14:36,973 --> 00:14:38,167
Free.

224
00:14:40,810 --> 00:14:42,038
I am free.

225
00:14:43,346 --> 00:14:44,779
You don't seem like it.

226
00:14:46,048 --> 00:14:47,640
Well, I am.

227
00:14:51,354 --> 00:14:52,651
I want to show you something.

228
00:14:52,822 --> 00:14:55,120
-What are you doing?
-Just come on.

229
00:14:56,058 --> 00:14:57,286
You'll get run over.

230
00:14:57,426 --> 00:14:58,950
By all the cars?

231
00:15:07,370 --> 00:15:12,433
My dad and I used to come out here and
lay down and watch the lights change.

232
00:15:12,742 --> 00:15:15,905
Watch them go from green
to red to yellow.

233
00:15:17,313 --> 00:15:19,975
You could try it if you wanted to.

234
00:15:20,116 --> 00:15:21,879
-No.
-Why not?

235
00:15:22,451 --> 00:15:25,579
Because-- I don't know.
Will you just get up?

236
00:15:25,721 --> 00:15:28,246
That's your problem. You know that?

237
00:15:29,425 --> 00:15:30,790
You don't do what you want.

238
00:15:39,035 --> 00:15:40,195
Ok.

239
00:15:58,120 --> 00:15:59,747
What happens if a car comes?

240
00:15:59,889 --> 00:16:00,856
You die.

241
00:16:01,023 --> 00:16:02,820
-What?
-Just relax.

242
00:16:02,959 --> 00:16:05,257
Just trust.
You need to learn how to trust.

243
00:16:07,830 --> 00:16:08,797
Ok.

244
00:16:12,301 --> 00:16:13,233
Painting.

245
00:16:14,370 --> 00:16:17,271
You asked me what I do for me.

246
00:16:18,174 --> 00:16:19,607
I love to paint.

247
00:16:20,276 --> 00:16:21,641
You?

248
00:16:25,748 --> 00:16:29,514
Most of the time I have all these
thoughts bouncing around in my head.

249
00:16:30,186 --> 00:16:35,123
But with a brush in my hand,
the world just gets kind of quiet.

250
00:16:43,899 --> 00:16:45,366
Get out of the street!

251
00:16:54,610 --> 00:16:55,599
Are you okay?

252
00:16:58,381 --> 00:16:59,905
Why are you laughing?

253
00:17:04,620 --> 00:17:05,780
That was fun.

254
00:17:10,726 --> 00:17:12,057
Do you want to dance with me?

255
00:17:13,496 --> 00:17:14,463
Sure.

256
00:17:17,600 --> 00:17:18,828
Now?

257
00:17:19,235 --> 00:17:20,133
Here?

258
00:17:21,604 --> 00:17:23,367
-Not supposed to dance in the street.

259
00:17:23,506 --> 00:17:25,303
-Supposed to dance in the street.

260
00:17:26,842 --> 00:17:28,104
We don't have any music.

261
00:17:28,244 --> 00:17:29,233
Well...

262
00:17:29,712 --> 00:17:31,202
...we'll make some.

263
00:17:50,332 --> 00:17:51,993
You're a terrible singer.

264
00:17:52,134 --> 00:17:52,998
I know.

265
00:17:55,404 --> 00:17:57,372
But I like this song.

266
00:18:50,526 --> 00:18:54,428
''Southern summers are indifferent
to the trials of young love.

267
00:18:54,563 --> 00:18:56,622
Armed with warnings and doubts...

268
00:18:56,765 --> 00:18:59,700
...Noah and Allie gave a remarkably
convincing portrayal...

269
00:18:59,835 --> 00:19:03,794
...of a boy and a girl traveling down
a very long road...

270
00:19:03,939 --> 00:19:06,134
...with no regard
for the consequences.''

271
00:19:06,275 --> 00:19:07,708
They fell in love, didn't they?

272
00:19:07,843 --> 00:19:10,403
-Yes, they did.
-Good.

273
00:19:10,546 --> 00:19:12,912
I like this kind of story. Go on.

274
00:19:18,187 --> 00:19:19,347
''After that night,

275
00:19:19,488 --> 00:19:22,946
Allie and Noah spent
every waking hour together.

276
00:19:23,092 --> 00:19:25,617
And soon, they were inseparable.''

277
00:19:26,262 --> 00:19:27,991
-Noah, come on!
-I'll beat you there.

278
00:19:28,130 --> 00:19:29,358
Come on!

279
00:19:30,633 --> 00:19:33,329
-That looks really nice.
-Try that. lt's really good.

280
00:19:38,641 --> 00:19:39,699
That's really nice.

281
00:19:48,450 --> 00:19:50,850
''--the primitive apples,
the pebble-stones

282
00:19:50,986 --> 00:19:52,681
Beautiful dripping fragments...

283
00:19:52,821 --> 00:19:56,757
...the negligent list of one
after another...

284
00:19:56,892 --> 00:20:00,919
...as I happen to call them to me
or drink to them...

285
00:20:01,063 --> 00:20:02,121
The real poems,

286
00:20:02,264 --> 00:20:04,994
(what we call poems
being merely pictures )

287
00:20:05,134 --> 00:20:07,500
The poems of the privacy
of the night...

288
00:20:07,636 --> 00:20:09,228
...and of men like me

289
00:20:09,371 --> 00:20:11,703
This poem, drooping shy and unseen...

290
00:20:11,840 --> 00:20:15,037
...that I always carry,
and that all men carry....''

291
00:20:15,177 --> 00:20:17,304
Not bad for Whitman.

292
00:20:17,746 --> 00:20:20,078
Hey, looks like you got a visitor.

293
00:20:20,950 --> 00:20:22,645
I'm sorry, I didn't mean to interrupt.

294
00:20:22,785 --> 00:20:25,618
Well, don't apologize.
Come on up here, darling.

295
00:20:25,955 --> 00:20:29,584
We could use a little something
around here besides the smell of lumber.

296
00:20:30,559 --> 00:20:32,151
-Dad, this is Allison Hamilton.

297
00:20:32,294 --> 00:20:34,524
-Allison, glad to meet you.
-Allie.

298
00:20:34,663 --> 00:20:36,392
-Allie.
-Pleased to meet you, Mr. Calhoun.

299
00:20:36,532 --> 00:20:40,059
-Am I old or something? Call me Frank.

300
00:20:40,202 --> 00:20:41,999
Hey, come in and have a seat.

301
00:20:43,772 --> 00:20:47,003
-Allie. Well, she is purty, son.
-Yes.

302
00:20:47,142 --> 00:20:49,007
She's a lot prettier than you let on.

303
00:20:49,144 --> 00:20:52,136
-Oh, is that right?
-No, it's not right. Don't believe him.

304
00:20:52,281 --> 00:20:53,111
What is this you got?

305
00:20:53,249 --> 00:20:56,377
I brought you something.

306
00:20:56,986 --> 00:20:58,817
Well, let's see. Let's have a look.

307
00:20:59,521 --> 00:21:01,512
Did you do this?

308
00:21:01,657 --> 00:21:03,056
Well, that's beautiful. Look at that.

309
00:21:03,192 --> 00:21:04,853
That's a damn picture there.

310
00:21:06,295 --> 00:21:07,853
Well,
I know just where we can put that.

311
00:21:07,997 --> 00:21:09,225
Thank you.

312
00:21:09,365 --> 00:21:13,199
That was a lovely poem. What was it?

313
00:21:13,335 --> 00:21:14,529
-Well--
-Whitman.

314
00:21:15,204 --> 00:21:18,833
See, when he was a little kid he used
to stutter real bad.

315
00:21:18,974 --> 00:21:20,771
-Dad.
-Well, you did.

316
00:21:21,343 --> 00:21:23,402
-I didn't know that.
-I stammered.

317
00:21:23,545 --> 00:21:25,206
Stammered, stuttered,
what's the difference?

318
00:21:25,347 --> 00:21:30,580
Couldn't understand him.
So I got him to reading poetry out loud.

319
00:21:31,120 --> 00:21:33,953
lt wasn't very pretty at first,
but then his stutter went away.

320
00:21:34,089 --> 00:21:36,853
-That's a good idea.
-Yeah, I thought so.

321
00:21:36,992 --> 00:21:39,927
Unbelievable. Unbelievable.

322
00:21:40,062 --> 00:21:43,190
I'm a Tennyson man myself
and he likes Whitman for some reason.

323
00:21:43,332 --> 00:21:44,196
I don't know.

324
00:21:44,333 --> 00:21:47,029
Say, how would you like some breakfast?

325
00:21:47,169 --> 00:21:48,466
-Breakfast?
-Yeah.

326
00:21:48,604 --> 00:21:50,128
Dad, it's 10:00.

327
00:21:50,272 --> 00:21:53,332
So? You can have pancakes any damn time
of the night you want.

328
00:21:53,475 --> 00:21:55,773
-Come on, you want some breakfast?
-Sure.

329
00:21:57,980 --> 00:22:00,642
''lt was an improbable romance.

330
00:22:00,783 --> 00:22:04,480
He was a country boy.
She was from the city.

331
00:22:04,720 --> 00:22:06,381
She had the world at her feet...

332
00:22:06,522 --> 00:22:09,150
...while he didn't have two dimes
to rub together.''

333
00:22:13,629 --> 00:22:15,119
Noah, come on!

334
00:22:18,367 --> 00:22:19,391
Look at them.

335
00:22:22,137 --> 00:22:23,263
What are we doing?

336
00:22:23,405 --> 00:22:25,839
You think in another life
I could have been a bird?

337
00:22:28,277 --> 00:22:29,301
What do you mean?

338
00:22:29,712 --> 00:22:31,270
Like reincarnation.

339
00:22:32,648 --> 00:22:33,876
I don't know.

340
00:22:34,650 --> 00:22:35,742
I think I could.

341
00:22:42,691 --> 00:22:43,919
Say I'm a bird.

342
00:22:44,927 --> 00:22:45,916
No.

343
00:22:46,462 --> 00:22:48,487
-Don't do it.
-Say I'm a bird.

344
00:22:48,630 --> 00:22:50,757
-Stop it. Stop it, now.
-Say it.

345
00:22:50,899 --> 00:22:52,491
-You're not.
-Say it!

346
00:22:54,203 --> 00:22:55,465
You're a bird.

347
00:23:02,644 --> 00:23:04,407
Now, say you're a bird too.

348
00:23:07,182 --> 00:23:08,649
If you're a bird, I'm a bird.

349
00:23:42,751 --> 00:23:44,776
-Come on, darling.
-What are you doing?

350
00:23:57,232 --> 00:23:59,063
On the count of three, okay?

351
00:23:59,201 --> 00:24:01,226
Real easy. On three. Ready?

352
00:24:01,370 --> 00:24:02,837
One.

353
00:24:02,971 --> 00:24:04,871
-Two.
-Two.

354
00:24:05,007 --> 00:24:06,770
-Three!
-No! I can't.

355
00:24:06,909 --> 00:24:08,206
Get in the water.

356
00:24:08,777 --> 00:24:10,176
-Come on, chicken.
-Get in!

357
00:24:10,312 --> 00:24:13,042
I'm sorry. Get in the water, baby.
Baby, would you get in.

358
00:24:13,182 --> 00:24:14,911
-Get in the water!
-I can't.

359
00:24:15,050 --> 00:24:16,574
-Just go!
-Get in the water!

360
00:24:16,718 --> 00:24:17,685
-One!
-Jump.

361
00:24:17,820 --> 00:24:20,084
-Two.
-Three!

362
00:24:32,434 --> 00:24:36,063
No, no, no. Get to a good place
and move!

363
00:24:36,205 --> 00:24:37,797
And keep it!

364
00:24:37,940 --> 00:24:40,534
I don't understand
what you're talking about!

365
00:24:41,143 --> 00:24:42,701
''They didn't agree on much.

366
00:24:42,845 --> 00:24:45,109
ln fact, they rarely agreed
on anything.

367
00:24:45,247 --> 00:24:47,010
They fought all the time.

368
00:24:47,149 --> 00:24:49,674
And they challenged
each other every day.

369
00:24:50,252 --> 00:24:54,848
But despite their differences they had
one important thing in common.

370
00:24:54,990 --> 00:24:57,390
They were crazy about each other.''

371
00:24:59,595 --> 00:25:00,823
Okay, I have to go.

372
00:25:00,963 --> 00:25:03,158
-No!
-Yes, I do.

373
00:25:16,845 --> 00:25:17,869
Allie.

374
00:25:18,113 --> 00:25:19,137
Daddy.

375
00:25:19,648 --> 00:25:23,550
Oh, Daddy, you--I didn't see you there.

376
00:25:24,353 --> 00:25:25,513
You kind of scared me.

377
00:25:28,690 --> 00:25:31,056
Awful friendly
with that boy down there.

378
00:25:33,495 --> 00:25:34,826
Yes.

379
00:25:36,398 --> 00:25:38,093
You bring him to the house on Sunday.

380
00:25:38,233 --> 00:25:40,030
I want to meet this young man.

381
00:25:42,237 --> 00:25:43,465
Night, Daddy.

382
00:25:44,139 --> 00:25:45,197
Good night.

383
00:25:52,314 --> 00:25:53,474
Oh, boy.

384
00:25:53,949 --> 00:25:56,713
This boy goes, ''Daddy,
I don't understand.'' He goes, ''Well...

385
00:25:56,852 --> 00:25:59,082
...in theory,
we're both millionaires...

386
00:25:59,221 --> 00:26:02,019
...but in reality we live
with a bunch of whores.''

387
00:26:06,495 --> 00:26:07,689
Bishop Stevens told me that.

388
00:26:07,829 --> 00:26:11,196
Olivia, remove the liquor decanter from
in front of my husband.

389
00:26:11,333 --> 00:26:12,960
He's had a little too much to drink.

390
00:26:15,604 --> 00:26:17,401
So, what do you do, Noah?

391
00:26:17,873 --> 00:26:20,433
I work at the lumberyard with Fin.

392
00:26:20,742 --> 00:26:24,803
Mainly milling and receiving logs
and stripping the bark.

393
00:26:25,514 --> 00:26:27,345
That's lovely, dear.

394
00:26:27,482 --> 00:26:27,971
Thank you.

395
00:26:28,116 --> 00:26:31,051
If you don't mind my asking,
how much do you earn?

396
00:26:31,186 --> 00:26:33,347
How much money do I make?

397
00:26:34,489 --> 00:26:36,684
Forty cents an hour.

398
00:26:40,228 --> 00:26:40,990
Yeah, it's not much,

399
00:26:41,129 --> 00:26:45,065
but I don't need a lot
and I save most of it.

400
00:26:47,202 --> 00:26:48,635
Let's eat, shall we?

401
00:26:48,770 --> 00:26:51,238
Oh, yes! Oh, it looks delicious.

402
00:26:53,875 --> 00:26:56,742
So, Noah, you and Allie been spending
a lot of time together.

403
00:26:58,814 --> 00:27:00,782
Must be very fond of each other.

404
00:27:02,951 --> 00:27:04,509
lt's getting pretty serious, huh?

405
00:27:06,421 --> 00:27:07,410
Yes, ma'am.

406
00:27:08,023 --> 00:27:09,923
Well, summer's almost gone.

407
00:27:10,492 --> 00:27:11,823
What will you do?

408
00:27:12,127 --> 00:27:14,493
Charleston's only a couple
of hours away.

409
00:27:17,032 --> 00:27:18,829
But Allie's going to Sarah Lawrence.

410
00:27:20,636 --> 00:27:22,069
Didn't she tell you?

411
00:27:22,437 --> 00:27:24,098
No, she didn't tell me that.

412
00:27:26,875 --> 00:27:28,968
I just got the letter.
I was going to tell you.

413
00:27:29,111 --> 00:27:30,078
lt's okay.

414
00:27:31,113 --> 00:27:32,705
And Sarah Lawrence is in New York.

415
00:27:37,486 --> 00:27:38,510
I didn't know that.

416
00:27:39,621 --> 00:27:42,886
Anne, this conversation's too stuffy
for the dinner table.

417
00:27:43,392 --> 00:27:44,324
Let the children have fun

418
00:27:44,459 --> 00:27:47,223
and no bringing
in the Spanish lnquisition.

419
00:27:47,562 --> 00:27:49,325
My lips are buttoned right now.

420
00:27:49,464 --> 00:27:53,662
I do know another joke about the nun
and the four stallions.

421
00:27:54,136 --> 00:27:57,003
Stop it. I'm leaving the table
if you tell another joke.

422
00:28:00,842 --> 00:28:03,174
Going to do it! Yeah!

423
00:28:03,512 --> 00:28:05,036
-No!
-Ready!

424
00:28:10,285 --> 00:28:13,482
That child's got too much spirit for a
girl of her circumstance.

425
00:28:13,622 --> 00:28:15,749
No, it's just a summer love.

426
00:28:15,891 --> 00:28:17,916
Trouble is what it is.

427
00:28:42,984 --> 00:28:44,281
Is that Allie out there?

428
00:28:48,156 --> 00:28:49,316
Do you want to go somewhere?

429
00:28:57,799 --> 00:28:58,788
Wait here.

430
00:29:19,888 --> 00:29:20,820
Allie!

431
00:29:23,225 --> 00:29:24,192
Come on.

432
00:29:28,930 --> 00:29:30,056
All right. Big step.

433
00:29:30,699 --> 00:29:31,961
Step. No, don't--

434
00:29:34,035 --> 00:29:35,366
All right, stay there.

435
00:29:36,371 --> 00:29:37,531
Don't open your eyes.

436
00:29:47,082 --> 00:29:48,310
The Windsor Plantation.

437
00:29:49,217 --> 00:29:51,378
lt was built in 1 772.

438
00:29:51,887 --> 00:29:57,587
Rumor has it that Francis Marion
proposed to his wife on these steps.

439
00:29:59,361 --> 00:30:02,194
Watch out. Be careful.
These are broken. Look at that.

440
00:30:03,865 --> 00:30:06,095
This place is gigantic.

441
00:30:06,234 --> 00:30:07,997
Yeah, a gigantic piece of crap.

442
00:30:09,237 --> 00:30:10,204
lt is.

443
00:30:10,705 --> 00:30:13,139
But I'm going to buy it one day.
I'm going to fix it up.

444
00:30:13,875 --> 00:30:15,604
All it needs is a new floor.

445
00:30:16,645 --> 00:30:19,705
-And new walls and roof.
-Is that all?

446
00:30:19,848 --> 00:30:21,941
And plumbing and electric.

447
00:30:22,083 --> 00:30:24,347
-And furniture.
-Yeah, and some furniture.

448
00:30:24,586 --> 00:30:26,053
But it's right on the water.

449
00:30:26,188 --> 00:30:29,555
And there's a big old barn up there.
I could turn that into my workshop.

450
00:30:29,858 --> 00:30:34,090
Well, what about me? Now,
don't I get any say in this?

451
00:30:35,831 --> 00:30:37,230
Do you want a say in this?

452
00:30:37,632 --> 00:30:38,894
Yes, I would.

453
00:30:40,402 --> 00:30:41,426
What do you want?

454
00:30:41,803 --> 00:30:45,398
I want a white house
with blue shutters...

455
00:30:45,540 --> 00:30:48,475
...and a room overlooking the river
so I could paint.

456
00:30:49,744 --> 00:30:51,075
-Anything else?
-Yes.

457
00:30:51,479 --> 00:30:54,778
I want a big old porch that wraps
around the entire house.

458
00:30:54,916 --> 00:30:58,010
And we can drink tea
and watch the sun go down.

459
00:31:01,756 --> 00:31:05,123
-You promise?
-I promise.

460
00:31:05,827 --> 00:31:06,555
Good.

461
00:31:08,029 --> 00:31:09,724
-Where you going?
-ln here.

462
00:31:59,881 --> 00:32:02,748
I can't play ''Chopsticks''
with you doing that.

463
00:32:25,473 --> 00:32:26,838
Make love to me.

464
00:34:21,623 --> 00:34:22,851
-Noah?
-Yeah?

465
00:34:25,360 --> 00:34:27,760
I know I said that
I wanted you to make love to me...

466
00:34:27,896 --> 00:34:30,990
...but I think you're going
to have to talk me through this.

467
00:34:33,401 --> 00:34:35,926
-Really? Everything?
-Yeah.

468
00:34:36,071 --> 00:34:37,698
-Did I hurt you?
-No, no.

469
00:34:37,839 --> 00:34:40,137
I'm just--
I'm just having a lot of thoughts.

470
00:34:40,275 --> 00:34:41,640
I'm just--

471
00:34:44,012 --> 00:34:45,138
Never mind.

472
00:34:51,519 --> 00:34:54,283
Like, what are you thinking?
What are you thinking right now?

473
00:34:54,422 --> 00:34:56,413
You know, right this second.

474
00:34:58,359 --> 00:35:01,351
Did you know that this would happen
when you brought me here?

475
00:35:02,063 --> 00:35:03,052
-No.
-No?

476
00:35:03,198 --> 00:35:05,166
No? You didn't think about it?

477
00:35:06,768 --> 00:35:09,032
-Of course I thought about it.
-You did?

478
00:35:09,170 --> 00:35:10,637
Well, what did you think?

479
00:35:12,040 --> 00:35:13,632
I'm talking too much, aren't l?

480
00:35:13,775 --> 00:35:16,209
Okay, I'm just going to shut up.

481
00:35:16,878 --> 00:35:17,970
Mum's the word.

482
00:35:20,982 --> 00:35:22,609
-You all right?
-Yeah.

483
00:35:24,586 --> 00:35:25,553
All right.

484
00:35:26,287 --> 00:35:29,256
I just don't understand
how come you're so quiet.

485
00:35:29,924 --> 00:35:31,824
You don't have one thought?

486
00:35:32,460 --> 00:35:36,260
I'm going crazy over here,
but, Noah, with you, everything's fine.

487
00:35:36,397 --> 00:35:38,422
You don't have a care in the world?

488
00:35:46,341 --> 00:35:47,774
Sorry.

489
00:35:48,243 --> 00:35:52,111
I wanted this to be so perfect
and now I can't shut up.

490
00:35:55,783 --> 00:35:57,216
I love you.

491
00:35:59,687 --> 00:36:00,619
Did you know that?

492
00:36:16,604 --> 00:36:17,730
I love you too.

493
00:36:33,922 --> 00:36:35,981
You don't have to do this
if you don't want to.

494
00:36:37,358 --> 00:36:40,293
No. No, I want to. I do.

495
00:36:41,696 --> 00:36:42,890
Noah!

496
00:36:43,031 --> 00:36:44,464
-Noah!
-What?!

497
00:36:44,866 --> 00:36:46,197
Fin, get out of here!

498
00:36:46,334 --> 00:36:48,802
Sorry, but Allie's parents
are going crazy.

499
00:36:48,937 --> 00:36:51,064
They got all the cops looking for her.

500
00:37:04,519 --> 00:37:06,214
-You sent the police for me?
-Yes.

501
00:37:06,354 --> 00:37:08,379
lt is 2 a.m. We sent the police.

502
00:37:08,523 --> 00:37:10,150
Thank God you're all right.

503
00:37:10,692 --> 00:37:11,659
Where you been?

504
00:37:11,793 --> 00:37:13,522
All this is my fault.

505
00:37:13,661 --> 00:37:15,526
Would you give us a moment, please?

506
00:37:15,863 --> 00:37:17,956
Like to talk to my daughter.

507
00:37:18,733 --> 00:37:20,530
Alone, young lady.

508
00:37:27,976 --> 00:37:30,911
-Thanks for everything, lieutenant.
-You bet, John. Anytime.

509
00:37:31,546 --> 00:37:34,014
You get straight home now. lt's late.

510
00:37:40,822 --> 00:37:44,258
Sir, it's really not her fault.
I lost track of time.

511
00:37:45,593 --> 00:37:46,582
Sit down.

512
00:37:57,872 --> 00:37:59,464
I'm sorry, Daddy.

513
00:37:59,607 --> 00:38:00,767
''I'm sorry, Daddy.''

514
00:38:00,908 --> 00:38:04,344
Think you can bat your eyelashes at
your father and get away with it?

515
00:38:04,479 --> 00:38:08,279
No. This time there's going to start
being some rules around here.

516
00:38:08,416 --> 00:38:09,212
Like what?

517
00:38:09,350 --> 00:38:11,318
If your father won't enforce them,
I will.

518
00:38:11,452 --> 00:38:12,350
Like what, Mother?!

519
00:38:12,487 --> 00:38:15,854
-You are going to stop seeing Noah.
-No.

520
00:38:15,990 --> 00:38:18,015
She is out fooling around
with that boy till 2 a.m.

521
00:38:18,159 --> 00:38:21,060
and it has got to stop.

522
00:38:21,195 --> 00:38:25,655
I din't spend 1 7 years raising
a daughter and giving her everything...

523
00:38:25,800 --> 00:38:27,893
...for her to throw it away
on a summer romance.

524
00:38:28,036 --> 00:38:30,630
She'll wind up broken-hearted
or pregnant.

525
00:38:30,772 --> 00:38:34,333
Now, he is a nice boy.
He's a nice boy, but he's...

526
00:38:34,475 --> 00:38:39,469
-He's what? He's what?! Tell me!
-He is trash! Trash! Not for you!

527
00:38:39,614 --> 00:38:42,378
-Trash?!
-He's a laborer. He's a woodworker.

528
00:38:42,517 --> 00:38:43,347
So what?!

529
00:38:43,484 --> 00:38:45,918
Are you going to live
in his father's house

530
00:38:46,054 --> 00:38:49,046
and pop out a few dirty kids?!

531
00:38:49,190 --> 00:38:50,817
I wouldn't mind!

532
00:38:50,958 --> 00:38:52,482
Don't touch me!

533
00:38:54,329 --> 00:38:56,456
You won't see him anymore. That's final.

534
00:38:56,597 --> 00:38:57,757
-No, it's not.
-Yes, it is.

535
00:38:57,899 --> 00:38:59,298
No, it's not final!

536
00:38:59,434 --> 00:39:01,800
You're not going to tell me
who I'm going to love!

537
00:39:01,936 --> 00:39:05,463
-Love?
-Yes, Daddy, I love him.

538
00:39:05,640 --> 00:39:07,130
I love him.

539
00:39:08,343 --> 00:39:10,504
He's not suitable for you, baby.

540
00:39:11,179 --> 00:39:15,047
I know he is not what you want for me.

541
00:39:15,183 --> 00:39:20,746
He's poor and unrefined and uncultured
and all wrong.

542
00:39:21,489 --> 00:39:22,751
I love him.

543
00:39:24,025 --> 00:39:27,483
-I love him.
-You know nothing about love.

544
00:39:27,628 --> 00:39:29,459
Oh, and you do?!

545
00:39:29,597 --> 00:39:31,861
You don't look at Daddy the way
I look at Noah.

546
00:39:31,999 --> 00:39:34,695
You don't touch or laugh.
You don't play.

547
00:39:34,836 --> 00:39:37,270
You don't know anything about love.

548
00:39:37,905 --> 00:39:38,894
Noah?

549
00:39:40,675 --> 00:39:41,642
Noah?

550
00:39:46,914 --> 00:39:47,881
You're leaving?

551
00:39:51,486 --> 00:39:54,182
I am so sorry.
I don't even know what to say.

552
00:39:54,322 --> 00:39:55,812
I'm humiliated.

553
00:39:56,491 --> 00:39:58,584
-lt's all right.
-No, it's not.

554
00:39:58,726 --> 00:40:01,194
-Yeah.
-No, it's not.

555
00:40:16,144 --> 00:40:19,113
-I'm going to go.
-No, I don't want you to go.

556
00:40:19,247 --> 00:40:22,478
-I got to think about some stuff.
-What do you got to think about, huh?

557
00:40:23,351 --> 00:40:24,943
Come here. Talk to me.

558
00:40:25,453 --> 00:40:26,579
Talk to me.

559
00:40:26,721 --> 00:40:28,188
About what? You want to--

560
00:40:29,257 --> 00:40:30,451
You're going away.

561
00:40:32,126 --> 00:40:33,252
You're leaving...

562
00:40:34,429 --> 00:40:35,521
...and I'm staying here.

563
00:40:37,398 --> 00:40:39,059
I'm so happy that you're doing that...

564
00:40:39,767 --> 00:40:41,962
...but you'll have
a million things to do.

565
00:40:42,103 --> 00:40:44,663
-You got so much ahead of you.
-Don't talk like that.

566
00:40:44,806 --> 00:40:45,864
lt's true.

567
00:40:46,007 --> 00:40:49,465
I'm not going to have nice things,
fancy things.

568
00:40:49,710 --> 00:40:51,075
lt doesn't--

569
00:40:52,146 --> 00:40:55,047
lt's never going to happen for me.
lt's not in the cards for me.

570
00:40:55,183 --> 00:40:57,276
-I don't have to go to school, okay?
-Yes, you do.

571
00:40:57,418 --> 00:40:58,908
-I can stay here
-No.

572
00:40:59,187 --> 00:41:00,620
That's exactly what I'm talking about.

573
00:41:00,755 --> 00:41:02,222
You can come with me.

574
00:41:03,658 --> 00:41:05,455
-To New York?
-Yes.

575
00:41:07,562 --> 00:41:09,154
what am I going to do in New York?

576
00:41:11,666 --> 00:41:12,928
Be with me.

577
00:41:18,272 --> 00:41:19,330
Yeah.

578
00:41:22,777 --> 00:41:23,835
I don't know.

579
00:41:29,383 --> 00:41:31,943
We don't got to figure
all this out tonight, you know?

580
00:41:32,086 --> 00:41:34,748
WE'll finish out the summer
and see what happens.

581
00:41:35,990 --> 00:41:37,924
Are you saying you want to break up?

582
00:41:38,459 --> 00:41:40,586
I'm saying we see how it goes later on.

583
00:41:47,168 --> 00:41:48,863
Are you breaking up with me?

584
00:41:52,006 --> 00:41:53,735
I don't see how it's going to work.

585
00:41:56,644 --> 00:41:57,633
I see.

586
00:41:59,647 --> 00:42:01,410
Please don't do this.

587
00:42:01,916 --> 00:42:03,281
You don't mean it.

588
00:42:04,585 --> 00:42:06,780
Oh, hell, well,
if you're going to do it,

589
00:42:06,921 --> 00:42:08,980
then why wait until the summer ends?

590
00:42:09,123 --> 00:42:11,489
Why don't you just do it right now?

591
00:42:13,160 --> 00:42:14,092
Come on.

592
00:42:14,629 --> 00:42:15,789
-Come on.
-What are you doing?

593
00:42:15,930 --> 00:42:17,056
Do it!

594
00:42:17,198 --> 00:42:18,165
Do it!

595
00:42:18,299 --> 00:42:19,789
Do it right now!

596
00:42:19,934 --> 00:42:21,026
Do it!

597
00:42:22,370 --> 00:42:23,530
Stop it!

598
00:42:24,839 --> 00:42:26,363
You know what?! I'll do it!

599
00:42:26,507 --> 00:42:28,805
lt's over! Okay?! lt's over!

600
00:42:29,710 --> 00:42:31,940
-Come here.
-Don't touch me!

601
00:42:32,280 --> 00:42:34,180
I hate you! I hate you!

602
00:42:34,315 --> 00:42:35,782
I'm going to go.

603
00:42:36,050 --> 00:42:38,644
Why don't you just go now!

604
00:42:38,786 --> 00:42:39,912
Leave!

605
00:42:40,187 --> 00:42:42,155
Go! Go!

606
00:42:43,891 --> 00:42:46,519
No, no.
We're not really breaking up, are we?

607
00:42:46,661 --> 00:42:48,959
This is just a fight we're having...

608
00:42:49,096 --> 00:42:52,031
...and tomorrow it'll be like
it never happened, right?

609
00:42:57,405 --> 00:42:57,962
Gone?

610
00:42:58,105 --> 00:42:59,333
Gone.

611
00:43:00,174 --> 00:43:02,836
-Well, she must've been devastated.
-She was.

612
00:43:03,477 --> 00:43:05,445
He was only trying to do
the right thing.

613
00:43:06,914 --> 00:43:12,011
But what he really should have done is
just told those parents to go to hell.

614
00:43:12,153 --> 00:43:14,986
Yeah, you're right. Probably should've.

615
00:43:17,191 --> 00:43:22,493
''The next day, Allie woke up to find
her world completely changed.''

616
00:43:29,637 --> 00:43:30,604
What's going on?

617
00:43:31,539 --> 00:43:33,063
We're going home.

618
00:43:34,108 --> 00:43:35,473
We're going now?

619
00:43:36,210 --> 00:43:38,440
We're not due to leave for another week.

620
00:43:38,579 --> 00:43:40,809
Get dressed and have some breakfast.

621
00:43:40,948 --> 00:43:44,475
-Will will pack your things.
-I'd be happy to pack your things.

622
00:43:44,619 --> 00:43:47,087
I don't want you to touch my stuff.

623
00:43:47,221 --> 00:43:48,051
I'm not going.

624
00:43:48,189 --> 00:43:50,453
-Yes, you are.
-No, I'm not.

625
00:43:50,591 --> 00:43:54,550
Well, yes, Allie, you are going whether
you like it or not.

626
00:43:54,895 --> 00:44:00,060
Now, even if Aaron has to drag
you the whole way, you're going.

627
00:44:07,375 --> 00:44:09,502
All right, let's go.
We have to have all these done by lunch.

628
00:44:09,644 --> 00:44:12,875
Quit standing around. Here we go.
Let's go! Come on!

629
00:44:19,720 --> 00:44:20,687
Where's Noah?

630
00:44:20,821 --> 00:44:22,345
He's out delivering a load.

631
00:44:23,691 --> 00:44:25,022
What's going on?

632
00:44:25,660 --> 00:44:26,786
I'm leaving town.

633
00:44:26,927 --> 00:44:28,519
Leaving? When?

634
00:44:28,663 --> 00:44:31,063
Now. Right now. Like, today.

635
00:44:32,733 --> 00:44:34,894
I need you to tell Noah something.

636
00:44:35,036 --> 00:44:37,197
Tell him that I love him
and tell him that

637
00:44:37,338 --> 00:44:39,533
I'm sorry for everything, okay?

638
00:44:39,674 --> 00:44:41,574
Look...

639
00:44:41,709 --> 00:44:43,609
...I was up all night with him, Allie.

640
00:44:43,744 --> 00:44:45,234
I've never seen him so low.

641
00:44:45,379 --> 00:44:48,371
lt's over. Don't make it any harder
than it already is.

642
00:44:48,516 --> 00:44:50,814
No. No, it's not over.

643
00:44:50,985 --> 00:44:54,045
We had a fight last night.
We said some things we didn't mean.

644
00:44:54,188 --> 00:44:55,951
-But it's not over.
-lt is over.

645
00:44:56,090 --> 00:44:58,217
Leave it alone. Let it go.

646
00:44:59,326 --> 00:45:02,227
I'm coming! Mama, I'm coming!

647
00:45:05,032 --> 00:45:06,499
Look...

648
00:45:06,634 --> 00:45:10,866
He understands.
lt's hard but he really does.

649
00:45:11,005 --> 00:45:13,132
When the summer's over,
it's time to go home.

650
00:45:13,674 --> 00:45:16,108
If he wants to talk to you,
he'll write. If not...

651
00:45:21,749 --> 00:45:26,880
Okay, can you just tell him that
I love him, then?

652
00:45:27,354 --> 00:45:28,548
Can you do that?

653
00:45:29,390 --> 00:45:30,482
I'll tell him.

654
00:45:35,663 --> 00:45:36,687
Bye, Fin.

655
00:46:19,240 --> 00:46:20,207
Go on.

656
00:46:35,022 --> 00:46:39,118
''Summer romances end
for all kinds of reasons.

657
00:46:40,027 --> 00:46:43,793
But when all is said and done,
they have one thing in common.

658
00:46:44,665 --> 00:46:46,462
They are shooting stars.

659
00:46:46,867 --> 00:46:49,995
A spectacular moment
of light from the heavens.

660
00:46:50,137 --> 00:46:52,037
A fleeting glimpse of eternity.

661
00:46:52,406 --> 00:46:54,169
And in a flash...

662
00:46:54,308 --> 00:46:55,468
...they're gone.

663
00:46:57,378 --> 00:46:59,039
Noah was desperate.

664
00:46:59,413 --> 00:47:03,577
He wrote to Allie that he was sorry
and stupid for breaking up with her.

665
00:47:03,717 --> 00:47:05,810
He wrote to tell her that
he still loved her

666
00:47:05,953 --> 00:47:07,477
and he wanted to see her.

667
00:47:07,621 --> 00:47:11,990
And that if she would write back,
he would come to wherever she was.

668
00:47:14,495 --> 00:47:19,626
He wrote one letter a day for a year.
365 letters.

669
00:47:19,767 --> 00:47:21,325
But they all went unanswered.''

670
00:47:21,468 --> 00:47:22,594
Hey, Fred!

671
00:47:23,270 --> 00:47:24,760
Nothing?

672
00:47:25,206 --> 00:47:26,230
Sorry.

673
00:47:26,373 --> 00:47:27,738
All right, thank you!

674
00:47:28,475 --> 00:47:30,238
''Finally, after a year of silence...

675
00:47:30,377 --> 00:47:34,177
...he decided to put it all behind him
and start a new life.

676
00:47:34,548 --> 00:47:36,448
So he wrote a farewell letter.

677
00:47:36,584 --> 00:47:40,884
And he and Fin packed their bags
and headed for Atlanta.''

678
00:47:42,556 --> 00:47:46,014
Noah!

679
00:47:46,260 --> 00:47:47,989
Come on! Listen to this!

680
00:47:48,128 --> 00:47:50,756
A state of war...

681
00:47:50,898 --> 00:47:53,332
...has existed...

682
00:47:53,467 --> 00:47:56,231
...between the United States and...

683
00:47:56,370 --> 00:47:58,634
''--Constitution of the United States...

684
00:47:58,772 --> 00:48:01,935
...against all enemies foreign
and domestic.''

685
00:48:02,076 --> 00:48:04,544
''Noah and Fin enlisted together.

686
00:48:04,678 --> 00:48:08,444
And after two years of chasing Rommel
through the North African desert...

687
00:48:08,582 --> 00:48:12,313
...they were deployed
to Patton's 3rd Army in Europe.''

688
00:48:28,235 --> 00:48:29,327
Fin!

689
00:48:53,794 --> 00:48:55,261
''Do I contradict myself?

690
00:48:56,130 --> 00:48:58,030
Very well then I contradict myself.''

691
00:48:58,165 --> 00:49:02,898
''Allie was in her third year of college
when she volunteered as a nurse's aide.

692
00:49:03,203 --> 00:49:07,503
To her, the broken men with shattered
bodies who filled the ward...

693
00:49:07,641 --> 00:49:09,074
...were all Noah...

694
00:49:09,209 --> 00:49:11,177
...or someone who fought beside him...

695
00:49:11,312 --> 00:49:14,543
...in the jungle
or a forzen snow-swept road.''

696
00:49:15,049 --> 00:49:17,415
Going to lift you up.
Ready?

697
00:49:18,252 --> 00:49:19,344
Good.

698
00:49:19,687 --> 00:49:20,745
There we go.

699
00:49:21,889 --> 00:49:23,379
We'll bring this leg over...

700
00:49:24,725 --> 00:49:25,851
...down.

701
00:49:25,993 --> 00:49:27,085
You okay?

702
00:49:28,595 --> 00:49:30,062
Miss...

703
00:49:30,331 --> 00:49:32,026
...can I ask you a question?

704
00:49:33,767 --> 00:49:35,735
I noticed that
you weren't wearing a ring...

705
00:49:35,869 --> 00:49:40,636
...and I was wondering
if I could take you out.

706
00:49:41,608 --> 00:49:42,939
Excuse me?

707
00:49:43,077 --> 00:49:44,339
Oh a date.

708
00:49:46,981 --> 00:49:49,745
Now, before you go and say no...

709
00:49:49,883 --> 00:49:53,319
...I'll have you know that
I am an excellent dancer...

710
00:49:53,454 --> 00:49:56,890
...and my intentions
are completely dishonorable.

711
00:50:01,028 --> 00:50:04,759
Okay, Casanova, come on.

712
00:50:05,032 --> 00:50:08,866
Let's just get you better,
then we'll talk about a date, okay?

713
00:50:18,979 --> 00:50:20,412
Would you get a load of him?

714
00:50:23,384 --> 00:50:26,376
Oh, my gosh, he is dreamy.

715
00:50:26,754 --> 00:50:27,914
What is he doing here?

716
00:50:28,055 --> 00:50:30,182
He's staring at you.

717
00:50:30,858 --> 00:50:31,825
Oh, miss?

718
00:50:34,028 --> 00:50:35,495
I'm all better.

719
00:50:37,097 --> 00:50:38,530
Now, how's about that date?

720
00:50:40,200 --> 00:50:44,136
''Allie was surprised how quickly
she fell in love with Lon Hammond.

721
00:50:49,043 --> 00:50:50,874
He was handsome, smart...

722
00:50:51,011 --> 00:50:53,844
...funny, sophisticated and charming.

723
00:51:02,222 --> 00:51:06,522
He also came from old Southern money
and was fabulously wealthy.''

724
00:51:11,298 --> 00:51:12,162
What?

725
00:51:21,775 --> 00:51:24,175
-We're going to dance.
-What's happening? Where are they going?

726
00:51:24,311 --> 00:51:26,745
-See you later, sweetheart.
-Look at that.

727
00:51:30,384 --> 00:51:32,944
I've been thinking about why
we shouldn't get married.

728
00:51:33,087 --> 00:51:35,578
I give up. Why shouldn't we get married?

729
00:51:35,722 --> 00:51:38,987
I couldn't think of anything at first.
Then it dawned on me.

730
00:51:39,126 --> 00:51:40,718
Your parents.

731
00:51:41,261 --> 00:51:45,027
-My parents?
-Absolutely. Dear old Mom and Dad.

732
00:51:45,566 --> 00:51:47,295
The problem is, is that they love me.

733
00:51:47,434 --> 00:51:50,062
-I'm the type they want you to marry.
-They do? Really?

734
00:51:50,204 --> 00:51:54,641
I'm wealthy, I'm from the South.
I've got a decent job.

735
00:51:54,775 --> 00:51:56,333
I'm an incredible dance.

736
00:51:56,477 --> 00:51:59,378
I'm a really smart guy.
You know, I'm very--

737
00:52:00,481 --> 00:52:03,507
-So, what's the problem?
-I like to think-- Just listen.

738
00:52:03,650 --> 00:52:05,345
If you marry me...

739
00:52:05,486 --> 00:52:07,420
Now, listen close.

740
00:52:07,554 --> 00:52:08,782
If you marry me,

741
00:52:08,922 --> 00:52:12,517
you'll lose a lifelong battle
in defiance against them.

742
00:52:12,659 --> 00:52:15,093
-Oh, my goodness, what will we do?
-I do not know.

743
00:52:16,029 --> 00:52:18,088
Hey, man, you feeling all right?

744
00:52:18,232 --> 00:52:20,462
Hey, man, you feeling all right?

745
00:52:24,404 --> 00:52:25,336
You say:

746
00:52:35,082 --> 00:52:38,347
See, Allie, I think-- Damn it,
I think you have to marry me.

747
00:52:38,485 --> 00:52:39,850
I think you need to marry me.

748
00:52:39,987 --> 00:52:41,011
-I do?
-Yes, you do.

749
00:52:41,155 --> 00:52:45,683
If you do, your parents'll always know
the unhappiness that you feel...

750
00:52:45,826 --> 00:52:47,555
...for not being able
to disappoint them.

751
00:52:47,694 --> 00:52:51,687
-You may have overlooked a minor detail.
-And what's that?

752
00:52:51,832 --> 00:52:54,699
Well, you see,
you have to get their permission first.

753
00:52:54,835 --> 00:52:58,168
And I think you may have overestimated
their affection for you.

754
00:52:58,305 --> 00:52:59,203
Is that right?

755
00:52:59,339 --> 00:53:00,863
Oh, I don't think so.

756
00:53:01,708 --> 00:53:02,572
Why not?

757
00:53:02,709 --> 00:53:04,939
I asked them already and they said yes.

758
00:53:05,812 --> 00:53:07,245
What?

759
00:53:10,450 --> 00:53:11,576
One more thing.

760
00:53:14,021 --> 00:53:15,045
I love you.

761
00:53:15,989 --> 00:53:17,388
Will you marry me, Allie?

762
00:53:18,358 --> 00:53:20,849
I know I kid around a lot,
but I am crazy about you.

763
00:53:23,096 --> 00:53:24,358
Marry me?

764
00:53:24,731 --> 00:53:25,993
Make me the happiest man in the world?

765
00:53:28,702 --> 00:53:29,669
Yes.

766
00:53:29,803 --> 00:53:31,031
Yes. Yes.

767
00:53:35,342 --> 00:53:36,866
-I'll tell them.
-Where you going?

768
00:53:39,680 --> 00:53:40,942
Mama!

769
00:53:42,082 --> 00:53:43,174
Stop th band.

